<p><b>Volume</b> is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mat=
hematics)" title=3D"Measure (mathematics)">measure</a> of <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Region_(mathematics)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"Region (mathematics)">regions</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Three-dimensional_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">three-dim=
ensional space</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST-2022_2-0" class=3D"reference"><=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-NIST-2022-2"><span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a><=
/sup> It is often quantified numerically using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit" title=3D"SI derived unit">SI derived units</a=
> (such as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_metre" title=
=3D"Cubic metre">cubic metre</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Litre" title=3D"Litre">litre</a>) or by various <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Imperial_units" title=3D"Imperial units">imperial</a> or <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/United_States_customary_units" titl=
e=3D"United States customary units">US customary units</a> (such as the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gallon" title=3D"Gallon">gallon</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quart" title=3D"Quart">quart</a>, =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_inch" title=3D"Cubic inch">c=
ubic inch</a>). The definition of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Length" title=3D"Length">length</a> and height (cubed) is interrelated with=
 volume. The volume of a container is generally understood to be the capaci=
ty of the container; i.e., the amount of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/wiki/Fluid" title=3D"Fluid">fluid</a> (gas or liquid) that the container =
could hold, rather than the amount of space the container itself displaces.=
=20
By <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metonymy" title=3D"Metonymy">me=
tonymy</a>, the term "volume" sometimes is used to refer to the correspondi=
ng region (e.g., <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bounding_volume" =
title=3D"Bounding volume">bounding volume</a>).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-3" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-3"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>2<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-4"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</spa=
n>3<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>In ancient times, volume was measured using similar-shaped natural c=
ontainers. Later on, standardized containers were used. Some simple <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Three_dimensional" class=3D"mw-redirect" =
title=3D"Three dimensional">three-dimensional</a> shapes can have their vol=
ume easily calculated using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arithm=
etic" title=3D"Arithmetic">arithmetic</a> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Formula" title=3D"Formula">formulas</a>. Volumes of more complicate=
d shapes can be calculated with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/In=
tegral_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Integral calculus">integral=
 calculus</a> if a formula exists for the shape's boundary. <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-dimensional_space" title=3D"Zero-dimensional=
 space">Zero-</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/One-dimensional=
_space" title=3D"One-dimensional space">one-</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Two-dimensional" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Two-dime=
nsional">two-dimensional</a> objects have no volume; in <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Four-dimensional_space" title=3D"Four-dimensional spa=
ce">four</a> and higher dimensions, an analogous concept to the normal volu=
me is the hypervolume.
</p>
