<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Ancient_history">Ancient hi=
story</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-brac=
ket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DVolume=
&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D2" title=3D"Edit section: Ancient history"=
><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span=
></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Pompeji_6_Hohlma%C3%9Fe_aus_Glas.jpg" class=
=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia=
/commons/thumb/8/8f/Pompeji_6_Hohlma%C3%9Fe_aus_Glas.jpg/250px-Pompeji_6_Ho=
hlma%C3%9Fe_aus_Glas.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"203" c=
lass=3D"mw-file-element" data-file-width=3D"2680" data-file-height=3D"2172"=
></a><figcaption>6&nbsp;volumetric measures from the <i>mens ponderia</i> i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pompeii" title=3D"Pompeii">Pompe=
ii</a>, an ancient municipal institution for the control of weights and mea=
sures</figcaption></figure>
<p>The precision of volume measurements in the ancient period usually range=
s between 10=E2=80=9350&nbsp;mL (0.3=E2=80=932&nbsp;US&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz; 0.4=
=E2=80=932&nbsp;imp&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-2016_5-0"=
 class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_n=
ote-Imhausen-2016-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=
=3D"Page: 8">:=E2=80=8A8=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The earliest evidence of vol=
ume calculation came from <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ancient_=
Egypt" title=3D"Ancient Egypt">ancient Egypt</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Mesopotamia" title=3D"Mesopotamia">Mesopotamia</a> as ma=
thematical problems, approximating volume of simple shapes such as <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cuboid" title=3D"Cuboid">cuboids</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cylinder" title=3D"Cylinder">cylinder=
s</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Frustum" title=3D"Frustum">=
frustum</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cone" title=3D"Con=
e">cones</a>. These math problems have been written in the <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Moscow_Mathematical_Papyrus" title=3D"Moscow Mathe=
matical Papyrus">Moscow Mathematical Papyrus</a> (c. 1820 BCE). In the <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Reisner_Papyrus" title=3D"Reisner Papy=
rus">Reisner Papyrus</a>, ancient Egyptians have written concrete units of =
volume for grain and liquids, as well as a table of length, width, depth, a=
nd volume for blocks of material.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-2016_5-1" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-=
Imhausen-2016-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"P=
age: 116">:=E2=80=8A116=E2=80=8A</span></sup> The Egyptians use their units=
 of length (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubit" title=3D"Cu=
bit">cubit</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Palm_(unit)" title=
=3D"Palm (unit)">palm</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Digit_(=
unit)" title=3D"Digit (unit)">digit</a>) to devise their units of volume, s=
uch as the volume cubit<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-2016_5-2" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-Imhausen-2=
016-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]=
</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 117">=
:=E2=80=8A117=E2=80=8A</span></sup> or deny (1 cubit =C3=97 1 cubit =C3=97 =
1 cubit), volume palm (1 cubit =C3=97 1 cubit =C3=97 1 palm), and volume di=
git (1 cubit =C3=97 1 cubit =C3=97 1 digit).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-20=
16_5-3" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume=
#cite_note-Imhausen-2016-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span=
 title=3D"Page: 117">:=E2=80=8A117=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>The last three books of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euc=
lid%27s_Elements" title=3D"Euclid's Elements">Euclid's <i>Elements</i></a>,=
 written in around 300 BCE, detailed the exact formulas for calculating the=
 volume of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parallelepiped" title=
=3D"Parallelepiped">parallelepipeds</a>, cones, <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Pyramid" title=3D"Pyramid">pyramids</a>, cylinders, and <a hr=
ef=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sphere" title=3D"Sphere">spheres</a>. T=
he formula were determined by prior mathematicians by using a primitive for=
m of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integral" title=3D"Integral">=
integration</a>, by breaking the shapes into smaller and simpler pieces. A =
century later, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes" title=
=3D"Archimedes">Archimedes</a> (<abbr title=3D"circa">c.</abbr><span style=
=3D"white-space:nowrap;">=E2=80=89287 =E2=80=93 212 BCE</span>) devised app=
roximate volume formula of several shapes using the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Method_of_exhaustion" title=3D"Method of exhaustion">meth=
od of exhaustion</a> approach, meaning to derive solutions from previous kn=
own formulas from similar shapes. Primitive integration of shapes was also =
discovered independently by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Liu_Hu=
i" title=3D"Liu Hui">Liu Hui</a> in the 3rd century CE, <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zu_Chongzhi" title=3D"Zu Chongzhi">Zu Chongzhi</a> in=
 the 5th century CE, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ea=
st" title=3D"Middle East">Middle East</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/India" title=3D"India">India</a>.
</p><p>Archimedes also devised a way to calculate the volume of an irregula=
r object, by submerging it underwater and measure the difference between th=
e initial and final water volume. The water volume difference is the volume=
 of the object. Though highly popularized, Archimedes probably does not sub=
merge the golden crown to find its volume, and thus its density and purity,=
 due to the extreme precision involved.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-6" class=3D"refe=
rence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-6"><span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>5<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up> Instead, he likely have devised a primitive form of a <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hydrostatic_Balance" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D=
"Hydrostatic Balance">hydrostatic balance</a>. Here, the crown and a chunk =
of pure gold with a similar weight are put on both ends of a <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weighing_scale" title=3D"Weighing scale">weighin=
g scale</a> submerged underwater, which will tip accordingly due to the <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Archimedes%27_principle" title=3D"Arc=
himedes' principle">Archimedes' principle</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-7" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-7"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>6<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p>
