with_graduated_cylinder_measuring_fluid_drams,_1926.jpg" class=3D"mw-file-d=
escription"><img alt=3D"Pouring liquid to a marked flask" src=3D"https://up=
load.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/2/2c/%22How_to_Measure%22_diagra=
m%2C_with_graduated_cylinder_measuring_fluid_drams%2C_1926.jpg/250px-%22How=
_to_Measure%22_diagram%2C_with_graduated_cylinder_measuring_fluid_drams%2C_=
1926.jpg" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"254" class=3D"mw-file-=
element" data-file-width=3D"1648" data-file-height=3D"1674"></a><figcaption=
>Diagram showing how to measure volume using a graduated cylinder with <a h=
ref=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fluid_dram" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Fluid dram">fluid dram</a> markings, 1926</figcaption></figure>
<p>In the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Middle_Ages" title=3D"Mi=
ddle Ages">Middle Ages</a>, many units for measuring volume were made, such=
 as the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sester" class=3D"mw-redire=
ct" title=3D"Sester">sester</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/inde=
x.php?title=3DAmber_(unit)&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;redlink=3D1" class=3D"new"=
 title=3D"Amber (unit) (page does not exist)">amber</a>, <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coomb_(unit)" title=3D"Coomb (unit)">coomb</a>, and =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seam_(unit)" title=3D"Seam (unit)"=
>seam</a>. The sheer quantity of such units motivated British kings to stan=
dardize them, culminated in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/As=
size_of_Bread_and_Ale" title=3D"Assize of Bread and Ale">Assize of Bread an=
d Ale</a> statute in 1258 by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Henry=
_III_of_England" title=3D"Henry III of England">Henry III of England</a>. T=
he statute standardized weight, length and volume as well as introduced the=
 peny, ounce, pound, gallon and bushel.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-2016_5-=
4" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite=
_note-Imhausen-2016-5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span titl=
e=3D"Pages: 73=E2=80=9374">:=E2=80=8A73=E2=80=9374=E2=80=8A</span></sup> In=
 1618, the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/London_Pharmacopoeia=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"London Pharmacopoeia">London Pharmacopoeia=
</a></i> (medicine compound catalog) adopted the Roman gallon<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-RPS-2020_8-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Volume#cite_note-RPS-2020-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> or <i><a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Congius" title=3D"Congius">congius</a></i><sup id=3D"cite=
_ref-9" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume=
#cite_note-9"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>8<span class=3D"cite-bra=
cket">]</span></a></sup> as a basic unit of volume and gave a conversion ta=
ble to the apothecaries' units of weight.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-RPS-2020_8-1" =
class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_no=
te-RPS-2020-8"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>7<span class=3D"cite-br=
acket">]</span></a></sup> Around this time, volume measurements are becomin=
g more precise and the uncertainty is narrowed to between 1=E2=80=935&nbsp;=
mL (0.03=E2=80=930.2&nbsp;US&nbsp;fl&nbsp;oz; 0.04=E2=80=930.2&nbsp;imp&nbs=
p;fl&nbsp;oz).<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Imhausen-2016_5-5" class=3D"reference"><a=
 href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-Imhausen-2016-5"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 8">:=E2=80=8A8=
=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Around the early 17th century, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Bonaventura_Cavalieri" title=3D"Bonaventura Cavalieri">Bonaventura Cava=
lieri</a> applied the philosophy of modern integral calculus to calculate t=
he volume of any object. He devised <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Cavalieri%27s_principle" title=3D"Cavalieri's principle">Cavalieri's prin=
ciple</a>, which said that using thinner and thinner slices of the shape wo=
uld make the resulting volume more and more accurate. This idea would then =
be later expanded by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pierre_de_Fer=
mat" title=3D"Pierre de Fermat">Pierre de Fermat</a>, <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Wallis" title=3D"John Wallis">John Wallis</a>, <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Barrow" title=3D"Isaac Barrow">=
Isaac Barrow</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Gregory_(m=
athematician)" title=3D"James Gregory (mathematician)">James Gregory</a>, <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Isaac_Newton" title=3D"Isaac Newton=
">Isaac Newton</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Wilh=
elm_Leibniz" title=3D"Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz">Gottfried Wilhelm Leibniz<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Gaetana_Agnesi" titl=
e=3D"Maria Gaetana Agnesi">Maria Gaetana Agnesi</a> in the 17th and 18th ce=
nturies to form the modern integral calculus, which remains in use in the 2=
1st century.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Metrication_and_redefinitio=
ns">Metrication and redefinitions</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.or=
g/w/index.php?title=3DVolume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4" title=3D"Ed=
it section: Metrication and redefinitions"><span>edit</span></a><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_th=
e_metric_system" title=3D"History of the metric system">History of the metr=
ic system</a></div>
<p>On 7 April 1795, the metric system was formally defined in French law us=
ing six units. Three of these are related to volume: the <i><a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/St%C3%A8re" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"St=C3=
=A8re">st=C3=A8re</a></i>&nbsp;(1&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>) for volume of firewoo=
d; the <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Litre" title=3D"Litre">l=
itre</a></i>&nbsp;(1&nbsp;dm<sup>3</sup>) for volumes of liquid; and the <i=
><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gram" title=3D"Gram">gramme</a></=
i>, for mass=E2=80=94defined as the mass of one cubic centimetre of water a=
t the temperature of melting ice.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-10" class=3D"reference=
"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-10"><span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>9<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> =
Thirty years later in 1824, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Im=
perial_gallon" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Imperial gallon">imperial gal=
lon</a> was defined to be the volume occupied by ten <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Pound_(mass)" title=3D"Pound (mass)">pounds</a> of water=
 at 17&nbsp;=C2=B0C (62&nbsp;=C2=B0F). This definition was further refined =
until the United Kingdom's <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weights=
_and_Measures_Act_1985" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Weights and Measures=
 Act 1985">Weights and Measures Act 1985</a>, which makes 1 imperial gallon=
 precisely equal to 4.54609&nbsp;litres with no use of water.<sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-11" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volu=
me#cite_note-11"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>10<span class=3D"cite=
-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The 1960 redefinition of the metre from the <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/International_Prototype_Metre" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=
=3D"International Prototype Metre">International Prototype Metre</a> to the=
 orange-red <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Spectral_line" title=
=3D"Spectral line">emission line</a> of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Krypton-86" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Krypton-86">krypton-86</a>=
 atoms unbounded the metre, cubic metre, and litre from physical objects. T=
his also make the metre and metre-derived units of volume resilient to chan=
ges to the International Prototype Metre.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-12" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-12"><sp=
an class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>11<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></=
a></sup> The definition of the metre was redefined again in 1983 to use the=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Speed_of_light" title=3D"Speed of=
 light">speed of light</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sec=
ond" title=3D"Second">second</a> (which is derived from the <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Caesium_standard" title=3D"Caesium standard">caes=
ium standard</a>) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2019_revisio=
n_of_the_SI" title=3D"2019 revision of the SI">reworded for clarity in 2019=
</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-13" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-13"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>12=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Properties">Properties</h2>=
<span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</sp=
an><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DVolume&amp;actio=
n=3Dedit&amp;section=3D5" title=3D"Edit section: Properties"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Further information: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume_elemen=
t" title=3D"Volume element">Volume element</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Volume_form" title=3D"Volume form">Volume form</a></div>
<p>As a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measure_(mathematics)" tit=
le=3D"Measure (mathematics)">measure</a> of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Three-dimensional_space" title=3D"Three-dimensional space">Eu=
clidean three-dimensional space</a>, volume cannot be physically measured a=
s a negative value, similar to <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Len=
gth" title=3D"Length">length</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Area" title=3D"Area">area</a>. Like all continuous <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Monotonic_function" title=3D"Monotonic function">monoto=
nic</a> (order-preserving) measures, volumes of bodies can be compared agai=
nst each other and thus can be ordered. Volume can also be added together a=
nd be decomposed indefinitely; the latter property is integral to <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cavalieri%27s_principle" title=3D"Cavalie=
ri's principle">Cavalieri's principle</a> and to the <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Infinitesimal_calculus" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"I=
nfinitesimal calculus">infinitesimal calculus</a> of three-dimensional bodi=
es.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-14" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-14"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>13<s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> A 'unit' of infinitesimally s=
mall volume in integral calculus is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Volume_element" title=3D"Volume element">volume element</a>; this for=
mulation is useful when working with different <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordinate syst=
ems</a>, spaces and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manifold" titl=
e=3D"Manifold">manifolds</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Measurement">Measurement</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DVolume&amp;act=
ion=3Dedit&amp;section=3D6" title=3D"Edit section: Measurement"><span>edit<=
/span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>The oldest way to roughly measure a volume of an object is using the hum=
an body, such as using hand size and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Pinch_(action)" title=3D"Pinch (action)">pinches</a>. However, the human=
 body's variations make it extremely unreliable. A better way to measure vo=
lume is to use roughly consistent and durable <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Container" title=3D"Container">containers</a> found in nature, =
such as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gourd" title=3D"Gourd">gou=
rds</a>, sheep or pig <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stomach" tit=
le=3D"Stomach">stomachs</a>, and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/U=
rinary_bladder" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Urinary bladder">bladders</a=
>. Later on, as <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metallurgy" title=
=3D"Metallurgy">metallurgy</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Glass_production" title=3D"Glass production">glass production</a> improved=
, small volumes nowadays are usually measured using standardized human-made=
 containers. This method is common for measuring small volume of fluids or =
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Granular_material" title=3D"Granul=
ar material">granular materials</a>, by using a <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Multiple_(mathematics)" title=3D"Multiple (mathematics)">mult=
iple</a> or fraction of the container. For granular materials, the containe=
r is shaken or leveled off to form a roughly flat surface. This method is n=
ot the most accurate way to measure volume but is often used to measure <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cooking_ingredient" class=3D"mw-redir=
ect" title=3D"Cooking ingredient">cooking ingredients</a>.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Air_displacement_pipette" t=
itle=3D"Air displacement pipette">Air displacement pipette</a> is used in <=
a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biology" title=3D"Biology">biology<=
/a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Biochemistry" title=3D"Bio=
chemistry">biochemistry</a> to measure volume of fluids at the microscopic =
scale.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-15" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-15"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>1=
4<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Calibrated <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measuring_cup" title=3D"Measuring cup">measuring =
cups</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Measuring_spoon" titl=
e=3D"Measuring spoon">spoons</a> are adequate for cooking and daily life ap=
plications, however, they are not precise enough for <a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Laboratory" title=3D"Laboratory">laboratories</a>. There=
, volume of liquids is measured using <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Graduated_cylinder" title=3D"Graduated cylinder">graduated cylinders</a=
>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pipette" title=3D"Pipette">pipe=
ttes</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volumetric_flask" tit=
le=3D"Volumetric flask">volumetric flasks</a>. The largest of such calibrat=
ed containers are petroleum <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Storag=
e_tank" title=3D"Storage tank">storage tanks</a>, some can hold up to 1,000=
,000&nbsp;<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barrel_(unit)#Oil_barrel=
" title=3D"Barrel (unit)">bbl</a> (160,000,000&nbsp;L) of fluids. Even at t=
his scale, by knowing petroleum's density and temperature, very precise vol=
ume measurement in these tanks can still be made.
</p><p>For even larger volumes such as in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia=
.org/wiki/Reservoir" title=3D"Reservoir">reservoir</a>, the container's vol=
ume is modeled by shapes and calculated using mathematics.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Units">Units</h3><span clas=
s=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DVolume&amp;action=3Dedit&a=
mp;section=3D7" title=3D"Edit section: Units"><span>edit</span></a><span cl=
ass=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main articles: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_of_volume" tit=
le=3D"Unit of volume">Unit of volume</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Orders_of_magnitude_(volume)" title=3D"Orders of magnitude (volu=
me)">Orders of magnitude (volume)</a></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb"><a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Visualisation_litre_gram.svg" class=3D"mw-fil=
e-description"><img src=3D"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/t=
humb/e/e9/Visualisation_litre_gram.svg/250px-Visualisation_litre_gram.svg.p=
ng" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"333" class=3D"mw-file-elemen=
t" data-file-width=3D"638" data-file-height=3D"850"></a><figcaption>Some SI=
 units of volume to scale and approximate corresponding mass of water</figc=
aption></figure>
<p>To ease calculations, a unit of volume is equal to the volume occupied b=
y a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_cube" title=3D"Unit cube"=
>unit cube</a> (with a side length of one). Because the volume occupies thr=
ee dimensions, if the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metre" title=
=3D"Metre">metre</a> (m) is chosen as a unit of length, the corresponding u=
nit of volume is the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cubic_metre" =
title=3D"Cubic metre">cubic metre</a> (m<sup>3</sup>). The cubic metre is a=
lso a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/SI_derived_unit" title=3D"SI=
 derived unit">SI derived unit</a>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-16" class=3D"referen=
ce"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-16"><span cla=
ss=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>15<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></su=
p> Therefore, volume has a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dimensi=
onal_analysis" title=3D"Dimensional analysis">unit dimension</a> of L<sup>3=
</sup>.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-17" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-17"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>=
16<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>The metric units of volume uses <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Metric_prefix" title=3D"Metric prefix">metric prefixes</a>, strictly i=
n <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Power_of_10" title=3D"Power of 1=
0">powers of ten</a>. When applying prefixes to units of volume, which are =
expressed in units of length cubed, the cube operators are applied to the u=
nit of length including the prefix. An example of converting cubic centimet=
re to cubic metre is: 2.3&nbsp;cm<sup>3</sup> =3D 2.3 (cm)<sup>3</sup> =3D =
2.3 (0.01 m)<sup>3</sup> =3D 0.0000023 m<sup>3</sup> (five zeros).<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-IBWM-2019_18-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-IBWM-2019-18"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>17<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"refe=
rence nowrap"><span title=3D"Page: 143">:=E2=80=8A143=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p><p>Commonly used prefixes for cubed length units are the cubic millimet=
re (mm<sup>3</sup>), cubic centimetre (cm<sup>3</sup>), cubic decimetre (dm=
<sup>3</sup>), cubic metre (m<sup>3</sup>) and the cubic kilometre (km<sup>=
3</sup>). The conversion between the prefix units are as follows: 1000&nbsp=
;mm<sup>3</sup> =3D 1&nbsp;cm<sup>3</sup>, 1000&nbsp;cm<sup>3</sup> =3D 1&n=
bsp;dm<sup>3</sup>, and 1000&nbsp;dm<sup>3</sup> =3D 1&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-NIST-2022_2-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-NIST-2022-2"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>1<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> The <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Metric_system" title=3D"Metric system">metri=
c system</a> also includes the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lit=
re" title=3D"Litre">litre</a> (L) as a unit of volume, where 1 L =3D 1&nbsp=
;dm<sup>3</sup> =3D 1000&nbsp;cm<sup>3</sup> =3D 0.001&nbsp;m<sup>3</sup>.<=
sup id=3D"cite_ref-IBWM-2019_18-1" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-IBWM-2019-18"><span class=3D"cite-bra=
