<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Capacity_and_volume">Capaci=
ty and volume</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=
=3DVolume&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D8" title=3D"Edit section: Capacit=
y and volume"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]=
</span></span></div>
<p>Capacity is the maximum amount of material that a container can hold, me=
asured in volume or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Weight" title=
=3D"Weight">weight</a>. However, the contained volume does not need to fill=
 towards the container's capacity, or vice versa. Containers can only hold =
a specific amount of physical volume, not weight (excluding practical conce=
rns). For example, a 50,000&nbsp;bbl (7,900,000&nbsp;L) tank that can just =
hold 7,200&nbsp;t (15,900,000&nbsp;lb) of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Fuel_oil" title=3D"Fuel oil">fuel oil</a> will not be able to conta=
in the same 7,200&nbsp;t (15,900,000&nbsp;lb) of <a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/wiki/Naphtha" title=3D"Naphtha">naphtha</a>, due to naphtha's low=
er density and thus larger volume.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Treese-2018_19-0" cla=
ss=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume#cite_note-=
Treese-2018-19"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>18<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup class=3D"reference nowrap"><span title=3D"P=
ages: 390=E2=80=93391">:=E2=80=8A390=E2=80=93391=E2=80=8A</span></sup>
</p>
